CREATE TABLE [dbo].[CustomerAddress](
	[CustomerID] [uniqueidentifier] NOT NULL,
	[AddressID] [int] NOT NULL,
	[AddressType] [nvarchar](50) NOT NULL)

```

## How it works (and fails) today

**Imagine we want to synchronization, per device, only customers belonging to one employee** .

Today, we can do something like that, in `Dotmim.Sync`:

```csharp
// On the server side, we had the filter
var filterClause1 = new FilterClause("Employee", "EmployeeID");
var filterClause2 = new FilterClause("Customer", "EmployeeID");

// On the client side, we had the SyncParameter for the device 
// Let's say we want only employee with ID = 1
var paramEmployee = new SyncParameter("Employee", "EmployeeID", 1)
var paramCustomer = new SyncParameter("Customer", "EmployeeID", 1)

```
It's fine for the `Employee` table and also for the `Customer` table.

But it won't work for the `Address` and `CustomerAddress`.
Eventually it will fail, because we should have in the `CustomerAddress` some rows that are referencing employees that are not present because of the filter.

## A solution to discuss

Ok, so we want to be able to sync all the tables linked (more or less) to one employee.

We have to refactor (and introduce some breaking changes, I guess) the `FilterClause` and `SyncParameter` classes, and the **SQL** generation as well.

### SyncParameter
In my mind, we should be able to inject a parameter, without any verification on its corresponding column on any table. This will allow us to create some **Virtual Parameter**

Since we don't have any resolution based on the name, this parameter should be:
- Typed on server side
- Just a Name / Value on client

On server side, let's say we can use a `DmColumn` to create this parameter, and use all the `DmColumn` properties to precise length, unicode, null, precision, scale ....
This column will be part of all `FilterClause` which need it

``` csharp
// Create the parameter that will be in the stored procedure parameter
var pEmpId = DmColumn.CreateColumn("empId", typeof(Int32));
pEmpId.AllowDbNull = true;
```
On client side, just set a `SyncParameter` with the correct name and its value

``` csharp
// We want all rows for the employee with EmployeeId = 1
var syncParameter new SyncParameter("empId", 1)
```

This parameter will generate a **SQL** variable, like `@empId int = null`

### FilterClause

Today the `FilterClause` creates a parameter that has the same name as the column name we want to filter.   
```csharp
var filterClause1 = new FilterClause("Employee", "EmployeeID");
```
Now that we have a `DmColumn`, with no restriction, the new `filterClause` will be something like

``` csharp
